## Parent epic
bd-3j4y — Adaptive routing policy engine

## Depends on
bd-1xrt (bd-v1r.7) — build_route_registry must accept topology + config before this wires it up

## Goal

Wire RoutingConfig and ResourceTopology into the actual startup sequence in listener.rs.
This is the integration bead that connects all the v1 routing work to the running server.

## CONTEXT: The actual startup sequence lives here

File: src/protocol/rest/listener.rs
Function: build_shared_state(config: &RestConfig) -> RefusalResult<Arc<RestSharedState>>

Current call sequence (lines ~252-293):
```rust
fn build_shared_state(config: &RestConfig) -> RefusalResult<Arc<RestSharedState>> {
    let catalog = load_rest_catalog(&config.spec_path)?;  // OpenApiDoc consumed here
    // ...
    let registry = build_route_registry(&catalog);          // no config, no topology
    // ...
}
```

The v1 call sequence must be:
```rust
fn build_shared_state(config: &RestConfig) -> RefusalResult<Arc<RestSharedState>> {
    // 1. Load spec (OpenApiDoc — do NOT consume yet)
    let (catalog, x_ext) = load_rest_catalog_with_extensions(&config.spec_path)?;
    //    ^ parse x-twinning BEFORE or DURING catalog build (see bd-v2s6 for approach)

    // 2. Resolve routing config from CLI + x-twinning extension
    let routing_config = resolve_routing_config(
        config.routing_policy,    // from RestConfig (added in bd-v1r.2)
        config.base_prefix.clone(),
        x_ext.as_ref(),
    );

    // 3. Build spec topology (global, all evidence sources)
    let topology = build_spec_topology(&catalog, &routing_config);

    // 4. Build route registry (topology lookup + waterfall fallback)
    let registry = build_route_registry(&catalog, &topology, &routing_config);

    // 5. Print startup routing report (confidence + conflict columns)
    let report = RoutingReport::from_registry(&registry);
    report.log_at_startup();

    // 6. Continue as before...
}
```

## Deliverables

### 1. Update RestSharedState (if needed)

If the topology needs to be available at request time (e.g. for debugging endpoints):
```rust
pub struct RestSharedState {
    pub catalog: Arc<RestCatalog>,
    pub routes: Arc<Vec<(Method, PathPattern, RouteEntry)>>,
    pub topology: Arc<ResourceTopology>,   // ADD if needed
    pub backend: Arc<Mutex<BaseSnapshotBackend>>,
    pub session_log: Arc<Mutex<RestSessionLog>>,
    pub session_ids: RestSessionIds,
}
```

Only add topology to RestSharedState if it's needed at request time. If only needed at startup, do not add it.

### 2. Update load_rest_catalog / build_rest_catalog

If the approach chosen in bd-v2s6 is to parse x-twinning inside build_rest_catalog and store it in RestCatalog:
- RestCatalog gets a new field: pub x_twinning: Option<XTwinningExt>
- load_rest_catalog() return type is unchanged
- x_ext is accessed via catalog.x_twinning

If the approach is to add extensions to OpenApiDoc:
- load_rest_catalog returns (RestCatalog, Option<XTwinningExt>)
- Caller (build_shared_state) passes x_ext to resolve_routing_config

Coordinate with bd-v2s6 implementer — they must agree on approach before this bead starts.

### 3. Tests

- integration test: start_test_server with a WireMock-style spec and x-twinning base-prefix — assert routes behind /__admin are classified at Pinned confidence
- integration test: start_test_server with Petstore — assert all routes High confidence, no warnings

## File

src/protocol/rest/listener.rs (primary)
src/protocol/rest/spec.rs (if RestCatalog gets x_twinning field)
src/config.rs (if RestConfig gets routing_policy field — coordinate with bd-v1r.2 implementer)

## Acceptance

cargo run -- rest --spec /tmp/petstore.yaml starts and prints the routing report with confidence column.
cargo run -- rest --spec /tmp/wiremock.yaml starts and shows Pinned for /__admin/* routes.
All existing REST integration tests still pass.
